# BeatBoard

A real-time rhythm game for the NXP FRDM-KL46Z (ARM Cortex-M0+), written in bare-metal C.

## Overview

Notes scroll along a fixed song timeline. The player presses one of two onboard buttons in time with each note, and the score updates live on the segment LCD. All gameplay runs on the board's onboard hardware: two buttons, two LEDs, and the segment LCD. No external components.

## Gameplay

- Two lanes, mapped to the onboard buttons (SW1 = lane 0, SW3 = lane 1).
- The matching lane LED lights about 200 ms before each note as a timing cue.
- Press within 100 ms of the beat for "perfect" (+100), within 250 ms for "good" (+50). A late press or a press with no nearby note is a miss and resets the combo.
- The LCD shows live score during play and the final score at the end.
- State cycle: MENU, COUNTDOWN, PLAYING, RESULTS, back to MENU.

## Architecture

Game logic lives in source/, split into seven modules:

| Module | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| main.c | Hardware init and the main loop (input, then game state), no blocking delays |
| timer.c | SysTick configured to fire every 10 ms; the single source of timing |
| input.c | Reads and debounces the two buttons, timestamps press events |
| notes.c | Stores the beatmap; matches presses to notes within a 250 ms window |
| score.c | Classifies hits (perfect/good/miss) and tracks score and combo |
| display.c | Drives the segment LCD and lane LEDs |
| game_state.c | The finite state machine and LCD redraws |

Timing is fully interrupt-driven: a 10 ms SysTick tick maintains a millisecond counter, and all scheduling reads from it, so the main loop never busy-waits. No RTOS, no dynamic allocation, no floating point.

## Authorship

The seven modules in source/ are my team's work. The SLCD driver (lcd.c / lcd.h) is course-provided (originally by Aaron Wilhelm). The board/, drivers/, CMSIS/, startup/, and utilities/ folders are the MCUXpresso-generated SDK, used as-is.

## Build and run

1. Open the project in MCUXpresso and build.
2. Connect the board via the OpenSDA USB port and flash.
3. Press SW2 (reset) once to start.
